<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06158200 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06158200 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SCHOOL; TAX; ELECTION; RESULT; ALAMEDA; COUNTY; NEIGHBORHOOD  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  While several Bay Area communities approved school improvement taxes Tuesday,voters in Alameda County's tiny Sunol Glen School District narrowly rejected ameasure to fix up their lone 1925-era school.;    Sunol Glen's Measure A wouldhave raised $1.3 million to upgrade the venerable school, which serves 206students in kindergarten through eighth grade, build a science laboratory,conduct an earthquake study and install a public address system.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SCHOOL DISTRICTS GO TO THE VOTERSSUNOL SCHOOL MEASURE FAILS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     But it just missed getting the two-thirds majority needed for passage. Thevote was 180 to 108, or 62.5 percent to 37.5 percent.;    It was so close thatSuperintendent Les Imel said he will recommend the board place the measure onthe ballot again in November.;    &quot;I think it'll pass next time,&quot; Imel said.&quot;We got out the 'no' votes already. Now we're going to work a lot harder toget out the 'yes' votes.&quot;;    School officials estimated Measure A would haveadded $60 to $70 to the average homeowner's tax bill.;    Imel said the oldschool still has some of the original electrical and plumbing systems, andthough he considers the building safe, he wants to renovate it rather thanmake repairs as things break.;    In other parts of the Bay Area, some townsapproved measures to improve their schools.;    In the San Mateo City SchoolDistrict, which also covers Foster City, more than 70 percent of voterssupported a $55 annual parcel tax, which will raise money to hire teachers,and a $33 million bond issue for school renovation.;    In Contra CostaCounty's Acalanes Union High School District, which includes Orinda,Lafayette, Moraga and parts of Walnut Creek, voters approved a $42 parcel taxfor school funding. The Orinda Union School District gave the nod to a $70parcel tax.;    In Benicia, voters narrowly approved a $29.5 million schoolbond measure to fund construction and renovation of school buildings.;    Inthe Sonoma County town of Graton, 68 percent of voters approved a $3 millionbond issue that will allow the Oak Grove Unified School District to build somenew classrooms.;    Voters in Morgan Hill agreed to let their school districtuse money from a 1972 tax increase to buy land and prepare a site for a newschool.;    But Sunol Glen wasn't the only district to reject school financingmeasures.;    Voters in Santa Clara County's Saratoga Union School Districtnarrowly rejected a $179 tax that would have been levied annually for fouryears on each parcel of land. The funds would have helped the district avoidprogram cuts, restore library services and make repairs. The measure receivedabout 63 percent of the vote, less than the two-thirds needed for passage.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910606  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  442  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday June 6, 199100158200,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>